'''Bara''' is a village in [[Rupnagar district|Rupnagar]] District in [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]], [[India]]. The village has mainly two Jatt Sikh surnames Chakkal and Heer and lies on the Rupnagar-[[Morinda, India|Morinda]] Road at the left bank of a seasonal monsoon rivulet called [[Budki Nadi]], about four kilometers south-west of the city [[Ropar]] and {{Convert|40|km|abbr=on}} northeast of [[Chandigarh]] on [[National Highway 205 (India)]] (NH-205). <ref name="ref38zalux">{{Citation | title=Gleanings of Indian archaeology, history, and culture |author1=K.D. Bajpai |author2=Rasesh Jamindar |author3=P. K. Trivedi |author4=Ramanlal Nagarji Mehta | publisher=Publication Scheme, 2000 | isbn=978-81-86782-64-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0gNuAAAAMAAJ | quote=''... Bara lies on the left bank of a monsoon rivulet known as Budki Nadi and is four kilometers southwest of Rupar. It is more known for Bara culture than the Mature phase of Harappa culture ...''|year=2000 }}</ref> Bara is the site of significant archeological excavations connected with the [[Indus Valley Civilization]].<ref name="ref14qefeh">{{Citation | title=Ancient Indian Social History: Some Interpretations | author=[[Romila Thapar]] | publisher=Orient Blackswan, 1978 | isbn=978-81-250-0808-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fK3VTUrWsD0C | quote=''... there appears to be a continuity of pre-Harappan cultures into the second millennium B.C. at sites in the Sutlej valley and the upper Saraswati (e.g. Bara and Siswal A) ...''| year=1978 }}</ref> It has some evidence of being home to a culture (sometimes called [[Bara culture|Baran Culture]]) that was a pre-Harappan strand of the Indus Valley Civilization.<ref name="ref14qefeh"/> Baran and Harappan cultures may have intertwined and coexisted in some places, such as [[Kotla Nihang Khan]], also in modern-day Punjab.<ref name="ref94logaf">{{Citation | title=Indian Archaeology in Retrospect: Prehistory, archaeology of South Asia |author1=Shadaksharappa Settar |author2=Ravi Korisettar | publisher=Indian Council of Historical Research, 2002 | isbn=978-81-7304-319-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iJzpAAAAMAAJ | quote=''... The mound at Kotla Nihang Khan is divided into two sectors: eastern and western. The eastern sector mainly has Urban Harappan pottery like the dish-on-stand, goblets with pointed base, shallow flat dish with flaring sides ... The western part has Urban Harappan elements mixed with Bara Ware from the lower levels. Sharma (1982: 141) thinks that ... initially, in Phase I, the Harappans occupied the eastern area, but with the advent of the Barans ...''|date=2002-01-01 }}</ref>
